Predicting Customer Churn

Carson Harris

2025-05-01

1 Problem Formulation & Data Understanding

1.1 Business Context

A major telecommunications company is experiencing customer churn, where some subscribers are choosing to cancel their service. This kind of attrition can be expensive because it generally cost more to acquire new customers than to retain existing ones. Churn can be caused by a number of factors including dissatisfaction with the service, increased competition, or unmet expectations. If not addressed, it can lead to a steady loss in revenue and customer base.

Predictive modeling offers a way to better understand and respond to this issue. By analyzing customer data such as demographics, billing information, and service usage, machine learning can identify which customers are most likely to leave. This allows the company to take action earlier through targeted offers or support. A well-performing model can help reduce churn and improve the efficiency of retention strategies.

1.2 Dataset Overview

The Telco Customer Churn dataset, sourced from IBM Sample Data Sets and available on Kaggle, provides information for analyzing customers behavior and predicting churn. It comprises 7,043 customers, each represented by a row with 21 columns capturing their attributes. Key features include whether a customer has churned, the services they have signed up for, account information, and demographic details. Although the specific time of the data collection is not provided, the dataset focuses on customers who left within the last month, allowing for targeted churn analysis. This dataset supports building machine learning models to identify at-risk customers and develop more targeted retention strategies.

2.3 Data Preprocessing

During data preprocessing, the primary focus was on handling missing values and preparing the target variable for analysis. Missing values in the TotalCharges column were estimated by multiplying MonthlyCharges by tenure, based on the assumption that they corresponded to newly acquired customers who had not yet been billed. The Churn column was converted from categorical (Yes/No) to binary format (1/0) to facilitate visualization and modeling. No additional encoding or feature transformation was applied at this stage to retain the datasets original structure for exploratory analysis.

#Cleaning missing or erroneous data
telcoCleanEDA <- telco %>%
  mutate(
    TotalCharges = if_else(is.na(TotalCharges), MonthlyCharges * tenure, TotalCharges),
    Churn = if_else(Churn == "Yes", 1, 0)  # encode target so you can plot
  )

The dataset is imbalanced, with significantly fewer customers churning compared to those who stayed, which is generally a good sign for the company. Churn appears more common among newer customers, especially within the first 24 months of tenure. Customers who churn also tend to have higher monthly charges, and the spread of those charges is more concentrated. Looking at service types, customers with fiber optic internet have the highest churn rate. When analyzing how many services a customer subscribes to, those with no services are the most likely to churn, likely due to low engagement. Churn rates are also somewhat higher among customers with two to four services. These patterns suggest that both service usage and cost play a role in predicting churn behavior.

3 Feature Engineering

3.1 New Feature Creation

#Creating new feature - TotalServices
telco <- telco %>%
  mutate(
    TotalServices = rowSums(select(., PhoneService, MultipleLines, OnlineSecurity, OnlineBackup, DeviceProtection, TechSupport, StreamingTV, StreamingMovies) == "Yes")
  )

A new feature was created to provide more insight into customer behavior. TotalServices captures the number of services each customer subscribes to by counting how many service-related fields are marked Yes which helps quantify overall customer engagement.

3.2 Feature Encoding

#Encoding features to be binary
cleaningTelco <- telco %>%
  mutate(
    gender = if_else(gender == "Female", 1, 0),
    Partner = if_else(Partner == "Yes", 1, 0),
    Dependents = if_else(Dependents == "Yes", 1, 0),
    PhoneService = if_else(PhoneService == "Yes", 1, 0),
    MultipleLines = if_else(MultipleLines == "Yes", 1, 0),
    dsl = if_else(InternetService == "DSL", 1, 0),
    fiberOptic = if_else(InternetService == "Fiber optic", 1, 0),
    OnlineSecurity = if_else(OnlineSecurity == "Yes", 1, 0),
    OnlineBackup = if_else(OnlineBackup == "Yes", 1, 0),
    DeviceProtection = if_else(DeviceProtection == "Yes", 1, 0),
    TechSupport = if_else(TechSupport == "Yes", 1, 0),
    StreamingTV = if_else(StreamingTV == "Yes", 1, 0),
    StreamingMovies = if_else(StreamingMovies == "Yes", 1, 0),
    OneYearContract = if_else(Contract == "One year", 1, 0),
    TwoYearContract= if_else(Contract == "Two year", 1, 0),
    PaperlessBilling = if_else(PaperlessBilling == "Yes", 1, 0),
    PaymentByMail = if_else(PaymentMethod == "Mailed check", 1, 0),
    PaymentByBankTransfer = if_else(PaymentMethod == "Bank transfer (automatic)", 1, 0),
    PaymentByCreditCard = if_else(PaymentMethod == "Credit card (automatic)", 1, 0),
    TotalCharges = if_else(is.na(TotalCharges), MonthlyCharges * tenure, TotalCharges),
    Churn = factor(Churn, levels = c("No", "Yes"))
  )

#Creating a new DF and selecting only numeric columns for modeling
numericTelco <- cleaningTelco %>%
  select(gender, SeniorCitizen, Partner, Dependents, tenure, TotalServices,
         PhoneService, MultipleLines, dsl, fiberOptic, OnlineSecurity, OnlineBackup,
         DeviceProtection, TechSupport, StreamingTV, StreamingMovies,
         OneYearContract, TwoYearContract, PaperlessBilling,
         PaymentByMail, PaymentByBankTransfer, PaymentByCreditCard,
         MonthlyCharges, TotalCharges, Churn)

All categorical features were encoded using binary dummy variables to prepare the data for modeling. One category from each feature was intentionally left out to serve as the reference group.

4 Model Selection & Training

4.1 Model Choice

Three models were selected to explore different approaches to predicting customer churn. Logistic regression was chosen for its simplicity and interpretability, providing insight into how each feature influence churn probability. A decision tree model was included to capture nonlinear relationships and provide a visual and rule-based structure for decision making. Lastly, a random forest model was used to improve predictive performance through ensemble learning and reduce the risk of overfitting by averaging across multiple decision trees.

4.2 Train-Test Split

#Splitting the data into training and testing
set.seed(123)

split <- sample(c(TRUE, FALSE), nrow(numericTelco), replace = TRUE, prob = c(0.7, 0.3))

train <- numericTelco[split, ]
test <- numericTelco[!split, ]

4.3 Train Models

For better results and to avoid overfitting, I tuned both the decision tree and random forest models using 5-fold cross-validation. For the decision tree, I tested different values of the complexity parameter to find the best balance between accuracy and simplicity. For the random forest, I tuned the mtry value using a custom grid. I looked at how accuracy changed across different values and chose the best setup based on that. This tuning helped make sure both models were well-optimized and ready to perform on new data.

For both models, tuning significantly impacted performance. The decision tree had the highest accuracy at a low complexity parameter, balancing model depth with interpretability. The random forest model performed best when mtry was set to 2, indicating that limiting the number of features considered at each split improved generalization and reduced overfitting.

5.3 ROC Curves and AUC

#Plotting ROC curves

## Area under the curve: 0.8451
auc(roc_tree)
## Area under the curve: 0.783
auc(roc_rf)
## Area under the curve: 0.837

Each model performed well, but there were clear differences in accuracy and interpretability. In terms of accuracy, logistic regression led at 80.5%, followed closely by random forest at 79.9%, and then the decision tree at 78.5%. The difference between logistic regression and the random forest was small, only 0.6 percentage points, suggesting both models performed similarly on overall classification.

However, comparing ROC curves and AUC highlighted more meaningful differences in each models ability to distinguish between those who churned and those who didnt. Logistic regression achieved the highest AUC at 0.8451, indicating strong overall discriminative ability. The random forest followed closely with an AUC of 0.8367, while the decision tree was lower at 0.783.

When it came to identifying actual churners, logistic regression achieved the highest sensitivity (recall) at 56%, meaning it correctly identified more of all customers who actually churned than the tree-based models, which were both around 47%. Thats roughly a 9 percentage point improvement in targeting customers likely to leave. However, when it came to precision, the random forest achieved the highest at 66.2%, meaning when it predicted a customer would churn, it was more correct more often that the other models. In other words, it produced fewer false alarms. Logistic regression followed at 64.6%, and the decision tree at 61.4%.

Overall, logistic regression was the strongest performer. While it had slightly lower precision than the random forest, it outperformed the other models in accuracy, discriminative power (AUC), and especially recall. Making it the most reliable option for identifying customers at risk of churning while minimizing false negatives. Although, it relies on the assumption of linear relationships in the data, logistic regression still delivered the most balanced and consistent performance across evaluation metrics.

6 Recommendations & Conclusion

6.1 Findings

Across all three models, several features consistently stood out as key drivers of churn. TotalCharges was among the most important predictors in each model. It was statistically significant in logistic regression, used as a top-level split multiple times in the decision tree, and ranked as the most impactful variable in the random forest based on MeanDecreaseGini. Based on the logistic regression coefficient, the odds of churning increase by approximately 0.029 percent for each additional dollar spent, holding all other variables constant. This translates to a 2.9 percent increase in the odds of churning for every one hundred dollar increase in total charges.

Contract type also played a major role. Customers on two year contracts were significantly less likely to churn, as shown by its strong negative coefficient in logistic regression and high importance in the random forest. It had an odds ratio of 0.276, meaning those with two year contracts were about 72.4 percent less likely to churn compared to customers with month to month plans.

Features related to service engagement, such as OnlineSecurity, TechSupport, and tenure, were also influential. TechSupport and OnlineSecurity were both negatively associated with reduced churn. Customers who use those services have odds of churning that are roughly 53 percent lower compared to those who do not. In addition, PaperlessBilling and fiber optic internet appeared frequently across models, suggesting that billing preferences and internet type may signal churn risk. These variables provide meaningful insight into which customer segments are most likely to churn and why.

6.2 Business Recommendations

Promote contract-based plans with incentives. Customers on one and two-year contracts are significantly less likely to churn, likely due to a combination of financial obligation and perceived value. Early termination fees discourage cancellation, but the model also suggests that customers on longer plans may feel more satisfied in their service. Offering incentives to switch from month-to-month to contract-based plans could help reduce churn while reinforcing customer loyalty.

Target high-charge customers with retention offers. Customers who churn tend to have higher monthly charges on average. This suggest that high-billing customers may be more price sensitive or dissatisfied with the value. Considering proactive retention strategies like bundling discounts or loyalty rewards for this segment could help reduce churn.

Improve and promote use of customer support services. Features like online security and tech support where negatively associated with churn, indicating that customers who engage with these services are more likely to stay. Investing in awareness campaigns and easier access to support could help reduce churn.

6.3 Limitations

This analysis is based on data from a single point in time, so it does not capture changes in customer behavior or services over time, which could be valuable for predicting churn more accurately.

The results show associations, not causation. We cannot definitively say any feature causes retention or churn without further experimental or longitudinal analysis.

6.4 Future Work

A time series dataset that tracks customer behavior over time would significantly enhance this analysis. It would allow for a more dynamic modeling of churn and help identify early warning signs. These signals could be used to identify customer at risk and trigger timely service interventions aimed at retention.

Conducting a randomized experiment or A/B test would also provide stronger evidence of causality by allowing us to evaluate the direct impact of specific features or interventions on churn outcomes.
